There are some problem with (Mismanaged plastic waste (tonnes)) variable in coast_vs_waste.csv, if I use this variable I got 13.8% of global mismanged plastic waste generate by China, but this also include OWID_WRL which is world average. If I exclude this observation, then China share jump to 27.8%

And if I use (Per capita mismanaged plastic waste (kg per day)) * population * 365 / sum(all indivual numbs), China share jump to 41.7%, I think the reason for such disparity is due to missing data, probabily there are missing valuein per_capita_missmaged or population cause such different. After checking the report on Ourworldindata I think I will use 27.8% method.

we can see the percentage of waste that are mismanaged are lower in high income countries and higher in low income country, and relationship are not linear.

Lets take a look at pre trade adjusted mismanaged plastic waste distribution globally.

And ths is pre adjusted trade data waste, we can now adjusted for trade. I assume, after transfer plastic waste back, countries will use their original % of plastic waste mismanagedment method to deal with this trade plastic waste.

## [1] "17.6%"

we can see if develope country dont export plastic trash to developing countries, instead landfill domestically, it will reduce total missmanged plastic waste by around 17.6% (if all my assumption were correct.)

Data analytical concludion:

  1. Global plastic waste production reach 270 million tons, China, U.S., and Germany are the primary produce count more than 40% of global plastic waste. (didnt expected germany be this high, since Euorpean take so much about envirornment)

2 Plastic waste per person have a linear relationship with gdp per capita, after log-log transformation.

  1. China import around 8 million tons plastic waste, count for 13.5% of China total plasic waste.

  2. After adjusted for plastic waste trade, the trend become more clear between income level and plastic waste per person. (Adjusted R increase, trned goes up)

Data analytical problem conclusion:

  1. Missing data will screw you in a way you least expected. Be very careful will dealing with missing data, it could screw all you analysis and conclusion.

  2. Put more attention to observation, in this case, some observation are not like others they are not countries but aggregate level such as world, OECD, asian, north amerca. It could also screw you analysis.
